SUMMARY:Housing Policy and Prospects of Upward Mobility: Evidence from So
 uth Korea
DESCRIPTION:Rising wealth inequality and worsening housing crises have in
 tensified economic grievances\, raising urgent questions about how access
  to housing carries political implications.  Soonhwan Kwon examines this 
 question by focusing on its role in shaping both economic security and we
 alth accumulation.  The study argues that policies expanding access to ho
 meownership‚ÄĒsuch as easing credit\, transaction\, and tax constraints i
 n the housing market‚ÄĒreshape individuals' prospects of upward mobility.
  Using a 2023 housing market deregulation in Seoul\, South Korea\, the pa
 per shows that these policies increase upward mobility prospects among ho
 meowners and higher-income renters\, while reducing them among lower-inco
 me renters. These findings suggest that housing policy shapes not only ec
 onomic inequality but also how individuals interpret their economic posit
 ion and the role of housing in wealth accumulation\, with unequal politic
 al implications across socioeconomic groups.Soonhwan Kwon is a Ph.D. stud
 ent in Political Science at Indiana University Bloomington\, specializing
  in comparative politics and political methodology. His research examines
  how housing policies reshape prospects of upward mobility and beliefs ab
 out housing as a source of wealth\, and how these processes relate to une
 qual political outcomes across socioeconomic groups.   A light lunch will
  be provided!&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Rising wealth inequality and worsening 
 housing crises have intensified economic grievances\, raising urgent ques
 tions about how access to housing carries political implications.</p><p> 
  Soonhwan Kwon examines this question by focusing on its role in shaping 
 both economic security and wealth accumulation.</p><p>  The study argues 
 that policies expanding access to homeownership‚ÄĒsuch as easing credit\,
  transaction\, and tax constraints in the housing market‚ÄĒreshape indivi
 duals' prospects of upward mobility. Using a 2023 housing market deregula
 tion in Seoul\, South Korea\, the paper shows that these policies increas
 e upward mobility prospects among homeowners and higher-income renters\, 
 while reducing them among lower-income renters. These findings suggest th
 at housing policy shapes not only economic inequality but also how indivi
 duals interpret their economic position and the role of housing in wealth
  accumulation\, with unequal political implications across socioeconomic 
 groups.</p><p><i></i></p><p><i>Soonhwan Kwon is a Ph.D. student in Politi
 cal Science at Indiana University Bloomington\, specializing in comparati
 ve politics and political methodology. His research examines how housing 
 policies reshape prospects of upward mobility and beliefs about housing a
 s a source of wealth\, and how these processes relate to unequal politica
 l outcomes across socioeconomic groups. </i></p><p>  A light lunch will b
 e provided!&#160\;</p>
