 ī–Ķ–Ĺ—ā–į –°–®–ź –≤ –Ĺ–Ķ–ī–į–≤–Ĺ–ł—Ö —Ā–ĺ–Ī—č—ā–ł—Ź—Ö.This lecture introd
 uces Belarus as a historical crossroads often overlooked in Western narra
 tives. Through a series of vivid snapshots\, it explores unexpected conne
 ctions from Gothic migrations and Viking trade routes to religious divers
 ity in the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth. It highlights Jewish intellect
 ual life\, Protestant movements\, and multicultural communities\, as well
  as links to American history\, including migration and industrial exchan
 ge. It traces how these legacies shape a modern tension between preserved
  Soviet legacy like collective farms and KGB and a highly developed digit
 al market forced out of the country. The lecture concludes by explaining 
 contemporary authoritarianism\, exiled government in the 21st century\, p
 rotests\, political prisoners\, and why U.S. engagement has played a tang
 ible role in recent developments.–Į –Ī–Ķ–Ľ–ĺ—Ä—É—Ā—Ā–ļ–ł–Ļ –į–ļ—ā–ł–≤–ł—Ā
