LOCATION:355 North Eagleson Avenue - Room Number: 2067
SUMMARY:IKS Colloquium - Youngho Cho
DESCRIPTION:IKS Spring 2026 Colloquium Series  Youngho Cho  Professor of 
 Political Science\, Sogang University.  "Self-coup crisis and Korean demo
 cracy"Friday\, April 1712:00-1:00pmHybridGISB 2067 | 355 N Eagleson AveZo
 om  &#160\;The former president of South Korea\, Yoon Seok-yeol\, declare
 d martial law on December 3\, 2024\, and immediately deployed airborne tr
 oops to the National Assembly in an effort to prevent legislators from vo
 ting to lift the declaration. Considered a typical case of a self-coup (a
 utogolpe) in comparative politics\, this attempt triggered a series of do
 mestic political crises. These crises appear to have concluded with Yoon 
 Seok-yeol's fall from the presidency\, his subsequent imprisonment\, and 
 the election of the current president\, Lee Jae-myung\, in June 2025.&#16
 0\;  &#160\;South Korea has long been regarded as an exemplary third-wave
  democracy\, despite several problems in the way its democratic system fu
 nctions. Why did Yoon Seok-yeol declare martial law? How was the self-cou
 p carried out? Why did it fail\, given that most self-coup attempts succe
 ed? What implications does this crisis hold for Korean democracy and for 
 other new democracies? My talk will attempt to answer these questions.  &
 #160\;  Open to the public. A light lunch will be served for in-person at
 tendees.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<h5 style="text-align: center\;">  IKS Sprin
 g 2026 Colloquium Series</h5><h6 style="text-align: center\;">  Youngho C
 ho</h6><p style="text-align: center\;">  Professor of Political Science\,
  Sogang University.</p><p style="text-align: center\;">  "Self-coup crisi
 s and Korean democracy"</p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Friday
 \, <span class="a_GcMg font-feature-liga-off font-feature-clig-off font-f
 eature-calt-off text-decoration-none text-strikethrough-none">April 17</s
 pan></strong></p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>12:00-1:00pm</st
 rong></p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Hybrid</strong></p><p st
 yle="text-align: center\;"><strong>GISB 2067 | 355 N Eagleson Ave</strong
 ></p><p style="text-align: center\;"><strong>Zoom</strong></p><p style="t
 ext-align: center\;">  &#160\;<span class="a_GcMg font-feature-liga-off f
 ont-feature-clig-off font-feature-calt-off text-decoration-none text-stri
 kethrough-none">The former president of South Korea\, Yoon Seok-yeol\, de
 clared martial law on December 3\, 2024\, and immediately deployed airbor
 ne troops to the National Assembly in an effort to prevent legislators fr
 om voting to lift the declaration. Considered a typical case of a self-co
 up (autogolpe) in comparative politics\, this attempt triggered a series 
 of domestic political crises. These crises appear to have concluded with 
 Yoon Seok-yeol's fall from the presidency\, his subsequent imprisonment\,
  and the election of the current president\, Lee Jae-myung\, in June 2025
 .</span>&#160\;</p><p style="text-align: center\;">  &#160\;<span class="
 a_GcMg font-feature-liga-off font-feature-clig-off font-feature-calt-off 
 text-decoration-none text-strikethrough-none">South Korea has long been r
 egarded as an exemplary third-wave democracy\, despite several problems i
 n the way its democratic system functions. Why did Yoon Seok-yeol declare
  martial law? How was the self-coup carried out? Why did it fail\, given 
 that most self-coup attempts succeed? What implications does this crisis 
 hold for Korean democracy and for other new democracies? My talk will att
 empt to answer these questions.</span></p><p style="text-align: center\;"
 >  &#160\;</p><p style="text-align: center\;">  Open to the public. A lig
 ht lunch will be served for in-person attendees.</p>
