SUMMARY:The Alchemy of Confidence
DESCRIPTION:This salon series at Indiana University features leading thin
 kers exploring how to build better digital and natural worlds.Beyond the 
 Web / After Analog Speaker Series.Why do we trust some signals‚ÄĒand fall
  for others?  Deception and honesty have long been locked in evolutionary
  arms races. From peacock feathers to social media profiles\, signals sha
 pe how we judge honesty and deception. But when false signals become wide
 spread\, trust breaks down‚ÄĒand only signals backed by real cost remain 
 credible.  This talk introduces signaling theory\, a powerful framework f
 or understanding:Why costly behaviors signal authenticity  How deception 
 spreads in human communication  What this means for disinformation and id
 entity in the digital age  How can technologies support trust and when do
 es it undermine it? As rapid technological change reshapes the incentives
  for deception and detection\, understanding the foundations of trust has
  never been more urgent.  Beyond signals alone\, we'll explore how trust\
 , social systems\, and oversight determine what‚ÄĒand who‚ÄĒwe believe.Ab
 out the Speaker  Judith is a writer\, designer and artist whose work focu
 ses on the co-evolution of technology and society. She has published nume
 rous articles about social media\, AI\, ethics and anonymity\, and is the
  author of The Social Machine: Designs for Living Online (http://amzn.to/
 NXFIFt) (MIT Press). As the former director of the MIT Media Lab's Sociab
 le Media Group\, she and her students designed innovative interfaces for 
 on-line communities\; their art projects examining the future of identity
 \, privacy and mediated life have been exhibited in museums and galleries
  worldwide.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  This salon series at Indiana University
  features leading thinkers exploring how to build better digital and natu
 ral worlds.</p><p><img src="https://vivatropolis.com/judith/JSD.CroppedSm  all.png" alt="" loading="lazy"/></p><p><strong data-olk-copy-source="Mess
 ageBody">Beyond the Web / After Analog Speaker Series.</strong></p><p dat
 a-start="131" data-end="466"><strong><em>Why do we trust some signals‚ÄĒa
 nd fall for others?</em></strong></p><p data-start="148" data-end="359"> 
  Deception and honesty have long been locked in evolutionary arms races. 
 From peacock feathers to social media profiles\, signals shape how we jud
 ge honesty and deception. But when false signals become widespread\, trus
 t breaks down‚ÄĒand only signals backed by real cost remain credible.</p>
 <p data-start="361" data-end="443">  This talk introduces <strong data-st
 art="382" data-end="402">signaling theory</strong>\, a powerful framework
  for understanding:</p><ul data-start="444" data-end="610"><li data-secti
 on-id="ukm1ns" data-start="444" data-end="488">Why costly behaviors signa
 l authenticity  </li><li data-section-id="di6nl5" data-start="489" data-e
 nd="537">How deception spreads in human communication  </li><li data-sect
 ion-id="hwujz7" data-start="538" data-end="610">What this means for <stro
 ng data-start="560" data-end="610">disinformation and identity in the dig
 ital age</strong></li></ul><p data-start="778" data-end="1319" data-is-la
 st-node="">  How can technologies support trust and when does it undermin
 e it? As rapid technological change reshapes the incentives for deception
  and detection\, understanding the foundations of trust has never been mo
 re urgent.</p><p data-start="778" data-end="1319" data-is-last-node="">  
 Beyond signals alone\, we'll explore how <strong data-start="652" data-en
 d="692">trust\, social systems\, and oversight</strong> determine what‚ÄĒ
 and who‚ÄĒwe believe.</p><p data-start="778" data-end="1319" data-is-last
 -node=""><strong>About the Speaker</strong></p><p data-start="778" data-e
 nd="1319" data-is-last-node="">  Judith is a writer\, designer and artist
  whose work focuses on the co-evolution of technology and society. She ha
 s published numerous articles about social media\, AI\, ethics and anonym
 ity\, and is the author of <i><a href="http://amzn.to/NXFIFt" target="_bl
 ank" rel="noopener">The Social Machine: Designs for Living Online</a></i>
  (MIT Press). As the former director of the MIT Media Lab's Sociable Medi
 a Group\, she and her students designed innovative interfaces for on-line
  communities\; their art projects examining the future of identity\, priv
 acy and mediated life have been exhibited in museums and galleries worldw
 ide.&#160\;</p>
